1
00:00:04,125 --> 00:00:06,267
Okay, looks like we're ready to get started.

2
00:00:06,847 --> 00:00:09,509
Just a quick message from all the guys in the red shirts,

3
00:00:09,549 --> 00:00:12,071
make sure you turn off your noisemakers,

4
00:00:12,111 --> 00:00:13,372
your phones, and everything else.

5
00:00:14,113 --> 00:00:15,434
And yeah, we'll get stuck into it.

6
00:00:17,335 --> 00:00:18,496
So my name's Luke Muscat,

7
00:00:18,637 --> 00:00:20,878
I'm the Chief Creative Officer at Halfbrick Studios.

8
00:00:21,119 --> 00:00:22,259
I've made these games.

9
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:24,621
People will probably know me best

10
00:00:24,681 --> 00:00:26,503
from Fruit Ninja and Jetpack Joyride.

11
00:00:27,493 --> 00:00:30,656
But today, I'm going to be talking about something else completely different.

12
00:00:30,756 --> 00:00:32,817
A game that no one here has played at all.

13
00:00:32,957 --> 00:00:35,499
It's only been played by 17 guys at Halfbrick.

14
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:37,861
And this talk is really a story.

15
00:00:38,381 --> 00:00:42,324
It's not going to be one of those talks that's full of lots of scientific facts

16
00:00:42,384 --> 00:00:44,285
and lots of, you know, really accurate graphs

17
00:00:44,486 --> 00:00:46,847
and do these things to make your game better.

18
00:00:46,947 --> 00:00:49,709
It's really, you know, a story about something that happened at work.

19
00:00:50,350 --> 00:00:50,450
And...

20
00:00:51,370 --> 00:00:54,813
I learned a lot from this thing happening to me,

21
00:00:54,893 --> 00:00:57,495
so I really hope that everyone else will get something else out of it too.

22
00:00:58,976 --> 00:01:01,137
So, just a quick disclaimer as I start.

23
00:01:01,317 --> 00:01:04,960
These are the guys from Halfbrick, and they are really, really great guys.

24
00:01:05,300 --> 00:01:08,802
Like, they are really the nicest bunch of people you'll ever meet.

25
00:01:09,603 --> 00:01:11,264
They're definitely not monsters,

26
00:01:11,564 --> 00:01:14,646
despite what I may or may not say in all of this presentation.

27
00:01:15,287 --> 00:01:16,247
Except for maybe Chevy.

28
00:01:18,289 --> 00:01:19,830
He's looking pretty monstrous right there.

29
00:01:21,963 --> 00:01:23,843
So a little bit of back story before I begin.

30
00:01:24,643 --> 00:01:27,764
So myself and one programmer and one artist

31
00:01:27,824 --> 00:01:28,864
worked on Fruit Ninja.

32
00:01:28,904 --> 00:01:31,304
And then we spent a long time updating that game.

33
00:01:31,344 --> 00:01:34,145
We were on it for almost two years just shipping updates.

34
00:01:34,725 --> 00:01:38,306
And finally, we managed to ship that off onto another team

35
00:01:38,346 --> 00:01:39,686
to work on all of the updates.

36
00:01:39,846 --> 00:01:42,166
And we were finally ready to do something new.

37
00:01:42,526 --> 00:01:44,767
We'd been so burnt out from working on the one thing

38
00:01:44,807 --> 00:01:45,387
for so long.

39
00:01:46,367 --> 00:01:47,887
So we started doing some prototyping.

40
00:01:47,987 --> 00:01:51,368
Here are a bunch of abandoned prototypes that we worked on.

41
00:01:51,835 --> 00:01:53,677
And you know, they were looking pretty good,

42
00:01:53,718 --> 00:01:54,899
and they were feeling pretty good,

43
00:01:54,979 --> 00:01:59,406
but we just weren't quite sure about what we were doing

44
00:01:59,526 --> 00:02:01,990
and whether we were on the right track.

45
00:02:02,611 --> 00:02:04,694
We really didn't have any goals or objectives

46
00:02:04,734 --> 00:02:06,436
to define our success.

47
00:02:07,748 --> 00:02:11,111
So we said, let's set some tougher goals. Let's come up with some tricky stuff.

48
00:02:11,532 --> 00:02:14,054
So the goal one was to make it massively multiplayer.

49
00:02:14,294 --> 00:02:19,380
By massively multiplayer, I don't mean, you know, a thousand-person server or anything like that.

50
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:22,963
But something that the whole company could play at once was the idea.

51
00:02:24,130 --> 00:02:26,893
The second one was to keep it really super simple to play.

52
00:02:27,714 --> 00:02:31,277
As you might expect from someone who's made a game about slicing fruit and

53
00:02:31,338 --> 00:02:35,642
spent ten months working on a one-button game, I really like simple stuff and

54
00:02:35,682 --> 00:02:37,484
really simple ideas and mechanics.

55
00:02:38,445 --> 00:02:42,088
This picture in the background is a flow chart from Warhammer 40,000 and I

56
00:02:42,168 --> 00:02:44,811
see that and my head just explodes.

57
00:02:46,712 --> 00:02:49,656
And the final goal, and the most important one for me,

58
00:02:49,696 --> 00:02:52,900
was to really get people in the office talking and engaged.

59
00:02:53,041 --> 00:02:56,906
And I really just wanted people to be super into this game

60
00:02:56,986 --> 00:02:58,688
and talking about it all of the time.

61
00:02:59,069 --> 00:03:00,631
And this was my, at any cost,

62
00:03:00,711 --> 00:03:03,134
I really wanna make sure people get engaged in the game.

63
00:03:04,954 --> 00:03:08,616
So for all of these really exciting goals and objectives,

64
00:03:09,056 --> 00:03:10,917
spent a bit of time, I worked with another designer

65
00:03:11,017 --> 00:03:12,818
called Joe Gatling for a while,

66
00:03:12,878 --> 00:03:14,900
and we came up with this amazing idea

67
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:16,620
that was gonna hit all of those goals,

68
00:03:17,141 --> 00:03:18,702
and it looked like this.

69
00:03:20,202 --> 00:03:23,824
It's made out of paper, sticky tape down onto a table.

70
00:03:23,965 --> 00:03:26,126
We wanted to do a massively multiplayer game,

71
00:03:26,146 --> 00:03:27,887
but it didn't really seem feasible for us

72
00:03:27,927 --> 00:03:30,508
to make a whole heap of backend infrastructure,

73
00:03:30,548 --> 00:03:33,230
so we did it all the old school way, pen and paper.

74
00:03:35,039 --> 00:03:38,222
So it was a 17 player, and it wasn't 17 player deliberately,

75
00:03:38,242 --> 00:03:41,324
I just simply asked who in the office wants to play this game,

76
00:03:41,344 --> 00:03:43,366
and we had exactly 17 people sign up.

77
00:03:44,027 --> 00:03:47,449
Real time strategy game with a really strong focus

78
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:49,231
on diplomacy and cooperation.

79
00:03:51,353 --> 00:03:52,794
So let me explain to you how it worked.

80
00:03:54,122 --> 00:03:56,502
This is a nice big close-up of what it looked like.

81
00:03:56,822 --> 00:03:57,862
These were your tanks.

82
00:03:58,143 --> 00:04:00,263
These were actually little pieces of

83
00:04:01,423 --> 00:04:03,544
magnetic whiteboard strips with marker on it.

84
00:04:04,264 --> 00:04:06,865
All the pages were just glued together onto the table,

85
00:04:07,025 --> 00:04:08,565
and that was how it was constructed.

86
00:04:08,765 --> 00:04:11,626
Very, you know, not fancy, not like Jason's

87
00:04:12,146 --> 00:04:15,327
titanium board game yesterday, that's for sure.

88
00:04:16,807 --> 00:04:17,707
And here are the rules.

89
00:04:18,107 --> 00:04:19,688
You have three hearts.

90
00:04:21,191 --> 00:04:24,172
And you are able to do basically two things by and large.

91
00:04:24,212 --> 00:04:25,932
You can either move or you can shoot.

92
00:04:26,612 --> 00:04:28,253
Both of these cost action points.

93
00:04:28,353 --> 00:04:30,893
So if you move one space, that costs one action point.

94
00:04:31,093 --> 00:04:33,454
And if you shoot, that costs one action point

95
00:04:33,554 --> 00:04:35,674
and will deduct one heart every time

96
00:04:35,754 --> 00:04:36,895
from whoever you shoot at.

97
00:04:37,375 --> 00:04:38,255
You have a range.

98
00:04:38,615 --> 00:04:41,996
The range is by default two, so quite close.

99
00:04:42,036 --> 00:04:43,776
It certainly wasn't a very wide range.

100
00:04:44,356 --> 00:04:47,677
You could also invest action points in upgrading your range.

101
00:04:48,941 --> 00:04:52,202
And the basic rule is, last player standing wins. Pretty simple.

102
00:04:53,302 --> 00:04:56,343
So the way action points work was, you know, we weren't going to be able to do this

103
00:04:56,443 --> 00:04:59,964
turn-by-turn with seventeen players, and to keep our objective of

104
00:05:00,084 --> 00:05:03,625
making it massively multiplayer, if we scaled it up to fifty people, that's just not

105
00:05:03,665 --> 00:05:04,225
going to work.

106
00:05:04,786 --> 00:05:08,107
So at the beginning of every single day, everyone gets an action point,

107
00:05:08,247 --> 00:05:11,248
and then you can spend those action points whenever you want. That's kind of

108
00:05:11,268 --> 00:05:13,688
how we resolved that many players issue.

109
00:05:14,368 --> 00:05:17,970
The action points are literally leftover badges we had from PAX.

110
00:05:18,550 --> 00:05:21,192
And you dropped them into a box with a hole cut in the top.

111
00:05:21,272 --> 00:05:22,792
And there was a little logbook next to it.

112
00:05:23,253 --> 00:05:25,174
And that was, you know, that was just...

113
00:05:25,454 --> 00:05:28,235
people would log what they were doing, and that way we knew no one was cheating.

114
00:05:29,696 --> 00:05:31,297
Very simple, very low-tech.

115
00:05:33,400 --> 00:05:37,543
And then the last rule was about trading. So you could send your action points to

116
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:41,304
someone else. And this is what was really interesting to me about the game.

117
00:05:41,645 --> 00:05:45,046
The way we visualized it was you couldn't just trade points with anyone

118
00:05:45,106 --> 00:05:48,388
on the board. You had to actually shoot that action point to them.

119
00:05:48,968 --> 00:05:51,669
So you had the same range as you did for attacking.

120
00:05:52,049 --> 00:05:55,090
So that way, anyone within your range is both friend and foe

121
00:05:55,110 --> 00:05:55,970
at the same time.

122
00:05:56,511 --> 00:05:59,191
You could potentially shoot that person, or you could help

123
00:05:59,231 --> 00:06:00,712
them out by giving them action points.

124
00:06:00,772 --> 00:06:03,092
And that was really the crux of what I thought would make

125
00:06:03,132 --> 00:06:04,373
this game very interesting.

126
00:06:05,733 --> 00:06:08,574
So just a really quick demonstration, just to clarify

127
00:06:08,614 --> 00:06:09,214
these rules.

128
00:06:09,274 --> 00:06:12,515
This is the grid, the yellow squares are the players.

129
00:06:12,815 --> 00:06:14,736
Every day, everyone gets an action point.

130
00:06:15,136 --> 00:06:16,736
In this case, one of the guys moves.

131
00:06:17,256 --> 00:06:18,357
That costs us an action point.

132
00:06:20,137 --> 00:06:23,221
One player trades over an action point, so now this player has two,

133
00:06:24,062 --> 00:06:25,785
and they shoot twice,

134
00:06:26,746 --> 00:06:28,629
which takes off those hearts.

135
00:06:29,370 --> 00:06:31,213
Next day, there's more action points.

136
00:06:31,253 --> 00:06:34,457
The player down the bottom, who has done nothing, has now collected two action points.

137
00:06:34,477 --> 00:06:36,059
You're not obligated to have to use them.

138
00:06:38,670 --> 00:06:42,774
And then the final thing about the game was there was a jury, and this was basically lifted

139
00:06:42,854 --> 00:06:43,895
straight from Survivor.

140
00:06:44,276 --> 00:06:48,601
It's a very similar idea. Dead players form a jury. I really wanted a way that

141
00:06:48,901 --> 00:06:51,484
dead players would still be involved and active in the game.

142
00:06:52,084 --> 00:06:55,728
And so the way this worked was every day the jury would vote for a player they

143
00:06:55,768 --> 00:06:56,449
wanted to help.

144
00:06:57,230 --> 00:07:00,291
And any player that got at least three votes from the jury

145
00:07:00,711 --> 00:07:03,072
would get an additional action point that day.

146
00:07:03,432 --> 00:07:05,432
So what this would do is, as the game kind of...

147
00:07:05,613 --> 00:07:07,753
more and more people died and the player base shrunk,

148
00:07:07,793 --> 00:07:09,854
it would accelerate the game towards a conclusion.

149
00:07:10,034 --> 00:07:10,714
That was the idea.

150
00:07:11,454 --> 00:07:16,616
And it also meant you couldn't just be a complete backstabbing bastard, right?

151
00:07:16,656 --> 00:07:18,437
Because you really need friends on the jury

152
00:07:18,497 --> 00:07:20,357
if you're going to win right, right at the end.

153
00:07:20,457 --> 00:07:21,578
Very similar to Survivor.

154
00:07:23,361 --> 00:07:26,925
So I kicked off the game. This is what it looked like. It was set up in a room,

155
00:07:26,945 --> 00:07:29,968
in a meeting room that happened to have glass walls,

156
00:07:30,729 --> 00:07:32,911
and I just sticky taped the rules up on the ball,

157
00:07:34,292 --> 00:07:37,115
told everyone how it worked, and I left and went to my desk.

158
00:07:37,295 --> 00:07:39,658
Gave everyone their first action point, and then I was done.

159
00:07:40,573 --> 00:07:43,815
And I was really thinking, you know, I wonder how long it's going to take someone

160
00:07:44,335 --> 00:07:49,378
to actually make a move in this game. I'm really expecting everyone to start hoarding their action points and

161
00:07:49,778 --> 00:07:54,580
you know, saving it up for right at the end and then it just being this crazy all-out thing that happens all at once.

162
00:07:55,967 --> 00:08:03,137
So, three hours later I'm sitting at my desk, and there's all this kind of commotion that I can hear from the other side of the room.

163
00:08:03,157 --> 00:08:04,960
And I'm like, what the hell is going on?

164
00:08:05,681 --> 00:08:10,989
And so I walk in to where the board is set up to check out what's going on, and it is a fucking graveyard in there.

165
00:08:13,092 --> 00:08:17,775
And not a graveyard in the sense that it's very quiet, a graveyard in the sense that a lot of players are dead.

166
00:08:18,696 --> 00:08:24,720
And immediately I'm like, what the hell is going on? I don't even understand how that could possibly happen so quickly.

167
00:08:24,760 --> 00:08:27,722
You guys all only have one action point. How did this happen?

168
00:08:29,043 --> 00:08:31,344
It turns out that there's definitely no one cheating.

169
00:08:32,045 --> 00:08:37,849
And the reason I was surprised was because the way I had designed the trading rules did not work the way I thought they would.

170
00:08:38,907 --> 00:08:42,830
This is what I had expected to happen on a bit of a bigger Zoom this time.

171
00:08:43,010 --> 00:08:44,671
I thought that what the trading rules would do

172
00:08:45,091 --> 00:08:47,473
would be localize them into little factions.

173
00:08:47,513 --> 00:08:50,775
You'd get little groups of 2, 3, 4, 5 people working together

174
00:08:51,296 --> 00:08:52,877
trying to get an advantage that way.

175
00:08:52,917 --> 00:08:55,699
Because, you know, alliances in this kind of game are really going to help.

176
00:08:56,719 --> 00:08:59,421
It turns out this is definitely not what happened at all.

177
00:09:00,578 --> 00:09:04,761
So this slide, just for reference, is all animated in PowerPoint,

178
00:09:04,861 --> 00:09:07,643
and it took me like two and a half hours to make this thing happen.

179
00:09:08,464 --> 00:09:11,727
So I'm really hoping it illustrates the point.

180
00:09:12,587 --> 00:09:14,189
So this is basically what happened.

181
00:09:15,230 --> 00:09:18,232
One player trades over his action point. This is what I expected.

182
00:09:18,292 --> 00:09:21,114
What I didn't expect is the chain that happened next.

183
00:09:21,555 --> 00:09:25,898
The second player passes both of those action points to the next player.

184
00:09:27,319 --> 00:09:28,080
And what happens?

185
00:09:29,295 --> 00:09:35,324
is through some incredibly advanced, incredibly complicated alliance-making.

186
00:09:42,259 --> 00:09:46,821
We managed to get this situation. This we immediately coined as daisy-chaining.

187
00:09:47,081 --> 00:09:51,543
That player now has nine action points. They could kill three players right now with that.

188
00:09:52,403 --> 00:09:55,965
And this is crazy. I mean, I can see how...

189
00:09:56,745 --> 00:10:00,227
Obviously the rules afford this happening, but there was no way I predicted it.

190
00:10:00,267 --> 00:10:04,528
I really thought what the trading rules were going to do would localize these little factions.

191
00:10:06,002 --> 00:10:11,125
So, I mean, everyone is running around pissed off and angry and confused,

192
00:10:11,245 --> 00:10:15,126
and some people are really excited because they managed to pull off this move.

193
00:10:15,226 --> 00:10:16,947
And I'm like, well, I guess that's a success.

194
00:10:17,027 --> 00:10:19,168
People are talking about the game. They're engaged.

195
00:10:19,769 --> 00:10:22,250
So, that part, yeah, all good.

196
00:10:23,830 --> 00:10:25,251
So a little bit further on now.

197
00:10:25,831 --> 00:10:29,013
This is day three. You'll see there are a lot of people in this room.

198
00:10:30,519 --> 00:10:34,966
The way that this was being designed, again, with the whole, you know, you can make your move at any time,

199
00:10:35,006 --> 00:10:38,752
was I was hoping it wouldn't interfere with work. You'd receive your action point.

200
00:10:39,132 --> 00:10:42,598
And then you could make your move any time during the day, whenever you have a spare moment.

201
00:10:43,704 --> 00:10:50,627
And now we're even at day three. We're at a point where there are so many people in this room, it's a good thing the walls are made of glass, because not everyone can fit in there.

202
00:10:51,927 --> 00:11:01,271
There's a really interesting thing. This photo doesn't demonstrate it quite as well, but just an interesting subtle thing that I only noticed when I was rehearsing this this morning,

203
00:11:01,731 --> 00:11:08,193
was that all the people in this image basically have their arms crossed, which is some interesting body language.

204
00:11:10,209 --> 00:11:13,354
So day five, things are getting crazier still.

205
00:11:13,595 --> 00:11:15,418
It's a little bit difficult to see in this photo,

206
00:11:15,478 --> 00:11:18,083
but you'll notice now I've added an extra page

207
00:11:18,283 --> 00:11:21,208
below the rules and it says cease fire, 9 a.m. till 10 a.m.

208
00:11:23,580 --> 00:11:28,143
The reason is, is people were so into this game that everyone was missing their morning scrums.

209
00:11:28,663 --> 00:11:30,044
Because they were down in the room.

210
00:11:30,645 --> 00:11:38,891
So I literally had to say, right, nothing, no actions allowed, 9am till 10am, get to scrum and do your work.

211
00:11:38,971 --> 00:11:42,854
You'll also notice the guy in the grey shirt in the middle is actually on crutches.

212
00:11:43,334 --> 00:11:44,495
He worked upstairs.

213
00:11:48,339 --> 00:11:53,055
He was hauling his ass down the stairs, up and down all the time on crutches to check

214
00:11:53,095 --> 00:11:54,500
out what's going on on the game board.

215
00:11:56,088 --> 00:12:00,692
And then things get even crazier. This is day seven. This is an SMS I got in the morning.

216
00:12:01,092 --> 00:12:03,113
This is our CFO, Renal.

217
00:12:03,594 --> 00:12:07,997
He was calling in sick that day, and he was so worried about the outcome of the game

218
00:12:08,037 --> 00:12:12,440
that he's asking me to veto his powers to another player called Biebs.

219
00:12:13,781 --> 00:12:17,123
He's going to love this. His name's Justin, so his nickname went from Bieber to Biebs.

220
00:12:17,784 --> 00:12:19,805
Because he was allowed to veto Bieber.

221
00:12:21,727 --> 00:12:25,608
And he's even got an image there attached of the game board from the previous days

222
00:12:25,668 --> 00:12:29,450
that he would be able to give very detailed instructions to that player

223
00:12:29,510 --> 00:12:32,371
to make sure that his move that day wouldn't be wasted.

224
00:12:33,132 --> 00:12:34,873
I mean, this is just getting crazy.

225
00:12:35,093 --> 00:12:38,914
And then, you know, I said, yeah, sure, okay, someone can play on your behalf.

226
00:12:38,994 --> 00:12:42,336
And it caused this massive uproar and it's... dramas.

227
00:12:43,783 --> 00:12:48,365
At this point I decided to do an anonymous survey. I wanted to find out a bit about what people were thinking.

228
00:12:48,465 --> 00:12:51,186
And no one would tell me anything. I would go up and ask people

229
00:12:51,686 --> 00:12:54,767
and they knew that I was trying to find out what was going on between players

230
00:12:54,807 --> 00:12:57,587
and everyone thought I was going to rat them out to the enemy.

231
00:12:57,607 --> 00:13:01,589
Because I was the only person across all the players.

232
00:13:01,649 --> 00:13:05,570
So the only way I could get any information out of them was through an anonymous survey.

233
00:13:05,790 --> 00:13:09,591
So I wanted to find out about two things. There was a lot of questions, but these were the interesting things.

234
00:13:11,250 --> 00:13:17,515
Diplomacy and interacting with other players is, and as you can see, extremely important to me, is way, way up there.

235
00:13:17,535 --> 00:13:21,738
So, great! I mean, you know, we wanted to make a game about cooperation, that seems to be working out just fine.

236
00:13:21,758 --> 00:13:26,262
The next one was engagement. I discussed the game with other players.

237
00:13:27,443 --> 00:13:29,344
Eleven plus times a day!

238
00:13:29,364 --> 00:13:35,309
This is just crazy. So again, I'm like, I'm feeling pretty good. This is a success, right?

239
00:13:35,329 --> 00:13:39,613
Like, I'm hitting all of the things that I wanted to hit with this prototype. Feeling great.

240
00:13:41,479 --> 00:13:46,462
So obviously with all of this going on, productivity in the workplace is going through the roof, right?

241
00:13:47,222 --> 00:13:49,924
Oh wait, no, the other thing. It's going way, way down.

242
00:13:50,344 --> 00:13:51,685
It's just disastrous.

243
00:13:52,025 --> 00:13:57,068
And other players are coming—sorry, not other players, other employees, not involved in the game,

244
00:13:57,168 --> 00:14:00,670
are telling me that this game is just tearing their teams apart.

245
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:03,131
Like, it's just massively disruptive.

246
00:14:03,491 --> 00:14:06,993
You know, they'll be looking for someone for a code fix, and the person can't be found.

247
00:14:07,334 --> 00:14:09,295
Probably should check where they're playing the game.

248
00:14:12,462 --> 00:14:15,024
So by day nine, things start to get pretty tense.

249
00:14:17,066 --> 00:14:19,267
And it's not even one particular thing.

250
00:14:19,408 --> 00:14:23,071
It's just this general feeling and vibe in the office.

251
00:14:23,211 --> 00:14:27,434
You really start to feel that there's some animosity between people from playing this game.

252
00:14:27,454 --> 00:14:30,217
There's people who would normally be very friendly,

253
00:14:30,457 --> 00:14:32,999
and they're looking over their shoulders, and they're paranoid,

254
00:14:33,419 --> 00:14:34,781
and it is just crazy.

255
00:14:35,982 --> 00:14:38,950
And you know, at this point, I'm still like kicking back and laughing.

256
00:14:38,991 --> 00:14:41,457
I'm like, oh my God, this is the best thing I've ever made.

257
00:14:41,477 --> 00:14:43,683
This is, this is so great.

258
00:14:46,802 --> 00:14:49,804
So then at some point, shit gets a little too real.

259
00:14:49,864 --> 00:14:52,586
And I didn't put a stupid Google image on this slide

260
00:14:53,126 --> 00:14:56,608
because I really don't want to downplay how serious this was.

261
00:14:56,688 --> 00:14:58,889
A player came to me and they were upset.

262
00:14:59,870 --> 00:15:00,870
Really, really upset.

263
00:15:00,970 --> 00:15:03,372
And they were like, this game, I feel at this point,

264
00:15:03,572 --> 00:15:07,434
is damaging the relationships I have at work,

265
00:15:07,554 --> 00:15:09,736
personal friendships I have with other people here,

266
00:15:09,836 --> 00:15:12,337
and generally making me not want to come to work

267
00:15:12,457 --> 00:15:13,418
and be involved in this.

268
00:15:14,963 --> 00:15:20,128
This is alarm bells, right? Like, this is not good. This was not the intention of the game at all.

269
00:15:20,989 --> 00:15:25,213
And this is pretty serious business, and we're hearing it from a couple of people, not just one person.

270
00:15:25,353 --> 00:15:30,037
One person in particular, but, you know, a lot of other people are starting to resonate with this as well.

271
00:15:31,339 --> 00:15:32,960
So at this point we shut down the game.

272
00:15:33,861 --> 00:15:37,644
Because, honestly, productivity in the whole office had come to a halt.

273
00:15:37,704 --> 00:15:41,228
People are getting upset. That's not what we want to happen at the office at all.

274
00:15:44,504 --> 00:15:48,208
So after that, I'm trying to figure out what made this happen.

275
00:15:48,328 --> 00:15:53,133
What turned a bunch of really nice people who normally play together really well...

276
00:15:54,488 --> 00:15:58,270
to do these kinds of things and to get so upset and worked up about the game.

277
00:15:58,331 --> 00:16:00,632
I just couldn't really understand.

278
00:16:01,012 --> 00:16:03,834
And I was trying to figure out—at first my response was, you know,

279
00:16:03,994 --> 00:16:06,636
ah, these guys, they're just taking it way too seriously.

280
00:16:06,676 --> 00:16:07,897
It's really all their own fault.

281
00:16:08,478 --> 00:16:11,159
But I really wanted to understand the mechanics of why this happened.

282
00:16:12,060 --> 00:16:14,221
And I'm in two minds, right? Like, on the one mind, I'm—

283
00:16:15,499 --> 00:16:18,501
Wow, I've made something amazing and powerful and incredible,

284
00:16:18,581 --> 00:16:22,423
and you know, it's a great story, and it's just this crazy cool thing.

285
00:16:22,784 --> 00:16:24,945
And the other mind, I'm really upset,

286
00:16:25,045 --> 00:16:27,987
because I've done something that's literally damaged the office.

287
00:16:28,007 --> 00:16:31,109
The office that I love and, you know, the people that I'm very close with,

288
00:16:31,929 --> 00:16:34,151
it's causing problems for them. So I feel terrible.

289
00:16:35,351 --> 00:16:38,313
And in a third mind, I'm like, maybe this will make a good GDC talk one day.

290
00:16:40,034 --> 00:16:43,837
So I do another survey to figure out what turned these guys into such monsters.

291
00:16:45,405 --> 00:16:48,226
And the first question asked is, you know, the game was exciting and compelling.

292
00:16:48,286 --> 00:16:52,367
And yeah, like, look at that. Overwhelmingly yes, the game was exciting and compelling.

293
00:16:52,467 --> 00:16:53,888
Great. That's fantastic.

294
00:16:56,289 --> 00:16:57,789
But this one's a bit more interesting.

295
00:16:57,989 --> 00:16:59,730
Start to ask a little bit tougher questions.

296
00:16:59,830 --> 00:17:01,330
The game made me feel paranoid.

297
00:17:01,670 --> 00:17:04,631
Almost 75% of people agree or strongly agree.

298
00:17:05,392 --> 00:17:09,133
And, I mean, I don't know about you guys, but paranoia I don't think is a positive feeling.

299
00:17:10,557 --> 00:17:14,820
And so then I asked a final question that was really a tough question, which was

300
00:17:14,840 --> 00:17:17,982
the game made me feel upset at times.

301
00:17:18,743 --> 00:17:20,043
And that was the response I got.

302
00:17:21,244 --> 00:17:25,167
Which to me was pretty incredible. Like more than half the players at some point

303
00:17:25,267 --> 00:17:26,668
felt upset in the game.

304
00:17:27,208 --> 00:17:30,550
And again, you know, I'm really not trying to make a game to upset people.

305
00:17:30,590 --> 00:17:33,832
I want them to be excited and I want them to be embracing the positives of the game

306
00:17:34,333 --> 00:17:36,254
and not really responding to the negatives.

307
00:17:38,218 --> 00:17:45,581
So I'm in two minds, you know, the game is a success in that I did manage to make something so compelling and so engaging.

308
00:17:45,741 --> 00:17:47,421
But on the other hand, it's a failure.

309
00:17:48,102 --> 00:17:53,323
Because I've done something that's hurt people and damaged people and been a detriment to the office.

310
00:17:53,883 --> 00:17:59,805
And again, at this point I'm still kind of like, ah, maybe it's those guys, they're just taking it too seriously and all of that.

311
00:18:01,182 --> 00:18:06,545
So I decided to launch an investigation to get a bit of better understanding why all this happened,

312
00:18:06,705 --> 00:18:08,166
more than just beyond a survey.

313
00:18:09,306 --> 00:18:14,389
I start going and talking to various people and really drilling down into

314
00:18:15,049 --> 00:18:19,751
what they were doing and what was happening behind the scenes that I couldn't see as an observer.

315
00:18:20,231 --> 00:18:24,834
And it turns out there was a lot happening behind the scenes that was completely invisible to me.

316
00:18:25,792 --> 00:18:29,657
And some of it is just way escalated beyond what I thought it would be.

317
00:18:30,437 --> 00:18:32,480
So this is one of the very first things I uncovered.

318
00:18:33,445 --> 00:18:35,707
Secret plans.

319
00:18:35,727 --> 00:18:39,990
So this is a secret plan put together by the artist of Fruit Ninja, Shaaf.

320
00:18:40,850 --> 00:18:43,272
And you can see this is a pretty complicated plan.

321
00:18:43,552 --> 00:18:48,656
This is involving a large amount of action points, moving through a very large amount of people.

322
00:18:49,016 --> 00:18:55,741
And then you can see the green numbers is displaying how many action points are in the pool at that particular time.

323
00:18:56,082 --> 00:19:02,626
And it's timed all the way down to killing Shaz, which is our boss, Shaneel Dio, with the very last action point.

324
00:19:04,025 --> 00:19:10,747
To think about how long it would have taken to coerce with so many players to make this plan happen is incredible.

325
00:19:11,248 --> 00:19:15,309
Like, that's a massive amount of organization and a massive amount of time effort.

326
00:19:15,349 --> 00:19:16,410
So this blew me away.

327
00:19:17,290 --> 00:19:21,772
But not as much as when I found this, which is the actual secret plan.

328
00:19:26,374 --> 00:19:29,955
So, the first secret plan was just to throw everyone else off the scent.

329
00:19:31,163 --> 00:19:35,466
This is the actual plan to take all of those action points from those players.

330
00:19:35,806 --> 00:19:38,568
They think they're about to take out all the guys on the left side

331
00:19:38,828 --> 00:19:41,790
and then turn around and backstab all the guys on the other side.

332
00:19:43,050 --> 00:19:47,313
So before I'd been thinking, wow, this is a lot of forethought, a lot of really, you know,

333
00:19:48,013 --> 00:19:52,496
really deep strategic stuff going on, and then it turns out it's like another layer deeper.

334
00:19:53,917 --> 00:19:55,538
This is just crazy, I love this.

335
00:19:57,822 --> 00:19:59,723
And so this was reflected in productivity.

336
00:19:59,863 --> 00:20:02,405
This is a quote from one of the guys at work, Fruity.

337
00:20:02,725 --> 00:20:04,606
Sorry, we use a lot of nicknames at Halfbrick,

338
00:20:04,626 --> 00:20:07,167
so all of these names sort of might seem a bit weird.

339
00:20:07,648 --> 00:20:08,848
So yeah, I would normally spend,

340
00:20:08,868 --> 00:20:11,610
normally have 11 or 12 tabs open in Spark,

341
00:20:11,650 --> 00:20:13,651
which is our little internal messaging program,

342
00:20:14,011 --> 00:20:16,772
talking about the game for up to six hours of the day,

343
00:20:17,373 --> 00:20:18,073
every day.

344
00:20:19,428 --> 00:20:22,010
So these guys actually sent me through a bunch of chat logs.

345
00:20:22,690 --> 00:20:25,552
Some of them are hilarious. I should put them up somewhere at some point,

346
00:20:25,592 --> 00:20:28,493
but I didn't have enough time to fit it all into this presentation.

347
00:20:29,034 --> 00:20:31,315
But there's one great one from Fruity,

348
00:20:32,075 --> 00:20:35,257
and he's talking to—he's got like nine conversations on the fly.

349
00:20:35,317 --> 00:20:36,738
It's really difficult to keep up with.

350
00:20:37,438 --> 00:20:37,999
And then he says,

351
00:20:38,019 --> 00:20:42,221
ah, okay, that's probably enough of that. I should probably actually get stuck into work.

352
00:20:42,341 --> 00:20:44,342
And the timestamp next to it says 3.30pm.

353
00:20:49,345 --> 00:20:51,246
And you know, people are getting so invested.

354
00:20:51,306 --> 00:20:52,286
This is another player.

355
00:20:52,306 --> 00:20:54,107
They've created this Excel sheet,

356
00:20:54,267 --> 00:20:56,788
and they're trying to track all the action points

357
00:20:56,868 --> 00:20:59,069
and which players they're with, and the two

358
00:20:59,129 --> 00:21:01,530
kind of different sides, understanding

359
00:21:01,570 --> 00:21:04,132
the total pool of action points they have available.

360
00:21:04,672 --> 00:21:08,054
So what this really shows is that, at this point,

361
00:21:08,574 --> 00:21:11,335
the main currency isn't really action points at all.

362
00:21:11,455 --> 00:21:12,276
It's information.

363
00:21:12,796 --> 00:21:14,857
That's what people are really trying to get to.

364
00:21:16,778 --> 00:21:18,138
And that leads us to spies.

365
00:21:19,595 --> 00:21:22,736
So let's say, hypothetically, there are two players playing the game

366
00:21:23,016 --> 00:21:26,477
and they're in the kitchen chatting about it and talking about their potential plans.

367
00:21:26,938 --> 00:21:28,558
And say there's a third person in there,

368
00:21:28,918 --> 00:21:31,759
not involved in the game at all, just quietly making a coffee.

369
00:21:32,779 --> 00:21:34,440
That person might overhear things

370
00:21:35,100 --> 00:21:37,701
and these things might be interesting to the players.

371
00:21:40,182 --> 00:21:42,923
So the players actually start recruiting spies.

372
00:21:45,488 --> 00:21:49,670
And there are up to five people who are not playing the game at all

373
00:21:50,010 --> 00:21:51,591
who are relaying information.

374
00:21:51,631 --> 00:21:55,213
And then there's even double agents who are feeding fake information.

375
00:21:55,233 --> 00:21:58,534
And it is just incredible. It's just getting out of control.

376
00:21:59,355 --> 00:22:02,456
And it sort of starts to explain why players who weren't even,

377
00:22:02,856 --> 00:22:05,298
sorry, employees who weren't even part of the game,

378
00:22:05,318 --> 00:22:07,879
where, you know, really their time was getting impinged on a lot.

379
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:12,761
And the spies thing gets even crazier somehow.

380
00:22:13,777 --> 00:22:18,319
So this is a really poorly drawn map, top-down, of one section of the office.

381
00:22:19,399 --> 00:22:24,041
All of the brown tables, sorry, brown squares there are tables where people sit at.

382
00:22:24,641 --> 00:22:26,682
The green one is where the game is set up.

383
00:22:27,823 --> 00:22:30,924
Those blue lines there, that shows where the walls of that office are,

384
00:22:30,984 --> 00:22:33,365
and those walls are made of glass, as I mentioned before.

385
00:22:33,505 --> 00:22:35,866
Turns out, this is an important point.

386
00:22:36,346 --> 00:22:38,307
Because if you were going to employ a spy,

387
00:22:39,728 --> 00:22:42,889
the people sitting at these desks can see that table all day long.

388
00:22:44,058 --> 00:22:46,279
they always know what's going on in the game

389
00:22:46,860 --> 00:22:50,082
they're just sitting there working away and if someone happens to walk into the

390
00:22:50,162 --> 00:22:52,964
office they can jump on and say hey guess what I think there's some shit

391
00:22:52,984 --> 00:22:53,564
going down

392
00:22:53,924 --> 00:22:57,107
you should probably jump over and check out and at first people were getting

393
00:22:57,167 --> 00:23:00,229
baffled by this they turn up to the room and then all of a sudden there's a crowd

394
00:23:00,249 --> 00:23:01,269
of like twenty people

395
00:23:02,010 --> 00:23:02,510
instantly

396
00:23:04,267 --> 00:23:08,569
is just, you know, and you know, at this point it's pretty obvious the game has kind of,

397
00:23:09,090 --> 00:23:11,731
it's not just a game anymore, it's infected the office.

398
00:23:12,352 --> 00:23:16,655
It's gone out of, it's not contained to this little room, it's running through the chat system, it's

399
00:23:17,595 --> 00:23:20,937
depending on where people are sitting in the office, it's just crazy.

400
00:23:23,659 --> 00:23:28,722
So then there's also things happening in the jury that I was completely blind to while the game was happening.

401
00:23:29,849 --> 00:23:33,834
Obviously, as I was saying, the jury is really important, because you want people to vote for you.

402
00:23:33,874 --> 00:23:37,519
That's how you are going to, you know, right at the end game, win the game.

403
00:23:37,979 --> 00:23:42,685
So it turns out there is an email thread among all the players running in secret.

404
00:23:43,626 --> 00:23:46,890
And in that email thread, people are running propaganda campaigns.

405
00:23:48,540 --> 00:23:53,083
and giving you reasons why you should give them action points and not other people action points

406
00:23:53,263 --> 00:23:53,884
and it's just

407
00:23:54,884 --> 00:23:58,327
again, it's just like this whole other level of strategy that I had no idea

408
00:23:58,367 --> 00:24:01,329
and it certainly wasn't part of the original intention with the design

409
00:24:03,350 --> 00:24:07,813
and then it starts getting even crazier. People create anonymous email accounts

410
00:24:08,273 --> 00:24:11,695
and they jump in on this thread and they're effectively poisoning the jury

411
00:24:11,735 --> 00:24:12,816
this one's pretty mild

412
00:24:12,896 --> 00:24:16,559
and you know, I've actually blacked out the names because I was talking to people about this

413
00:24:16,659 --> 00:24:16,959
and they've

414
00:24:17,639 --> 00:24:17,959
they felt

415
00:24:18,753 --> 00:24:20,934
deeply ashamed about what they were doing here.

416
00:24:21,515 --> 00:24:24,136
Because they're saying, you know, like, don't trust this person.

417
00:24:25,157 --> 00:24:27,918
And that might be one thing, but when you're in an office environment

418
00:24:28,599 --> 00:24:31,561
and you're saying, you know, I'm not saying don't trust

419
00:24:32,161 --> 00:24:32,901
Game Master 69.

420
00:24:33,202 --> 00:24:36,704
This person's saying, don't trust Luke Muscat.

421
00:24:37,284 --> 00:24:38,045
He's a bastard.

422
00:24:39,606 --> 00:24:42,968
And so that's, you know, that's getting personal. That's very personal at that point.

423
00:24:45,309 --> 00:24:48,331
So what was it about the game that made everyone go crazy, I wondered?

424
00:24:49,574 --> 00:24:53,015
definitely the context is a big deal. I mean, I'm certainly not blind to that.

425
00:24:53,055 --> 00:24:56,036
The fact that it happened in the office, among friends,

426
00:24:56,476 --> 00:24:58,717
that's going to make a really big change to it.

427
00:24:58,997 --> 00:25:00,698
But I don't think that's the entire blame.

428
00:25:01,018 --> 00:25:05,059
I mean, we play games at Halfbrick all of the time, constantly.

429
00:25:05,079 --> 00:25:09,120
That's mostly what we do. We play video games, we play poker every Friday night,

430
00:25:09,160 --> 00:25:10,981
we've had three-month-long 500 tournaments.

431
00:25:13,022 --> 00:25:14,803
Every game you can imagine, we've played it,

432
00:25:15,524 --> 00:25:17,746
and it's never had an effect like this on The Office.

433
00:25:18,026 --> 00:25:20,709
So in this case, I really don't think the context can be blamed.

434
00:25:20,749 --> 00:25:24,793
I think the context is just an amplifier that increased everything that happened.

435
00:25:27,255 --> 00:25:29,517
The time investment, I think, was a really big thing too.

436
00:25:30,178 --> 00:25:32,881
Don't you love how literal Google image search is sometimes?

437
00:25:32,901 --> 00:25:37,765
You're gonna search time investment and you get a clock sitting on the word investing.

438
00:25:39,915 --> 00:25:44,117
I mean, by the time you've put in five or six or seven days worth of

439
00:25:44,758 --> 00:25:47,919
work into this game, you know, you've built up these relationships

440
00:25:48,320 --> 00:25:51,381
even though, like, at first it's just this arbitrary thing and it's just little

441
00:25:52,001 --> 00:25:55,803
pieces of paper sliding around, some other paper, they begin to develop meaning.

442
00:25:56,244 --> 00:25:58,465
The time really, really makes a big difference.

443
00:26:00,366 --> 00:26:04,127
But then I think there were some really key rules that really set this whole thing off.

444
00:26:04,168 --> 00:26:05,868
I'm going to go through a couple of them really quick.

445
00:26:07,756 --> 00:26:11,059
The daisy-chaining implications is really, I think, the biggest culprit here.

446
00:26:11,239 --> 00:26:13,801
So this is the same image as before,

447
00:26:14,602 --> 00:26:16,463
just with arrows so you can see it visually.

448
00:26:16,903 --> 00:26:20,667
So what's interesting in most games, if you decide you don't want to be a part of an alliance,

449
00:26:20,727 --> 00:26:22,228
fine, you're out of that alliance.

450
00:26:22,308 --> 00:26:24,850
And you know, it might have been a four-person alliance before,

451
00:26:24,990 --> 00:26:27,632
but now you're on the edge and it's a three-person alliance.

452
00:26:28,533 --> 00:26:32,596
But look what happens in this game if you decide you don't want to be a part of the alliance.

453
00:26:33,791 --> 00:26:35,953
This purple player here has decided to opt out.

454
00:26:36,634 --> 00:26:38,716
They have completely destroyed this chain.

