00:39:42,140 --> 00:39:44,863
And during that hour, you have to be 100% focused.

686
00:39:44,903 --> 00:39:46,564
You get that time investment effect.

687
00:39:47,915 --> 00:39:51,597
and you know if you're playing a game of Counter-Strike or whatever you could play a game for an hour

688
00:39:51,637 --> 00:39:55,939
but you might cycle through a whole set of players and you know people dropping in and dropping out

689
00:39:55,999 --> 00:39:57,980
but that can't happen in League of Legends

690
00:39:58,640 --> 00:39:59,100
not at all

691
00:39:59,721 --> 00:40:03,102
in there the players are leveling up and so you know if someone's been playing for half an hour

692
00:40:03,142 --> 00:40:04,143
and then they drop out

693
00:40:04,403 --> 00:40:07,645
I mean what are you going to do? Add a new player that's back on level one?

694
00:40:07,685 --> 00:40:08,765
That's not going to work out

695
00:40:11,287 --> 00:40:12,968
and every player is a vital link.

696
00:40:13,268 --> 00:40:16,410
And again, this really reminded me of the whole peer pressure kind of thing,

697
00:40:16,670 --> 00:40:17,550
but in a different way.

698
00:40:19,712 --> 00:40:24,074
With only five players per team, if someone isn't performing at their best,

699
00:40:24,094 --> 00:40:26,896
you know, say they're only playing at half their ability,

700
00:40:26,976 --> 00:40:31,018
that takes your team from a hundred percent effective to ninety percent effective.

701
00:40:31,438 --> 00:40:35,181
And that's a big deal, you know, the team is really relying on every player to play

702
00:40:35,261 --> 00:40:38,623
well and do well to win in the game, and you want to win.

703
00:40:39,043 --> 00:40:42,445
Because you're putting a whole hour of unbroken time into that game.

704
00:40:45,106 --> 00:40:51,089
But more than all of this, I think what is really the crux of it is the underpinning structure

705
00:40:51,109 --> 00:40:56,252
of the game experience. And that's what I think creates such intensity in the player behavior.

706
00:40:56,292 --> 00:40:58,953
And I want to use the word intensity here, not toxicity.

707
00:40:59,773 --> 00:41:02,515
Because the intensity means, you know, you get those really toxic players,

708
00:41:02,775 --> 00:41:05,196
but then you get the guys who just love the game and, you know,

709
00:41:05,236 --> 00:41:07,257
do really great things in the community as well.

710
00:41:08,510 --> 00:41:13,476
So I think what it comes down to is this. There's a really big positive feedback loop in this game.

711
00:41:13,797 --> 00:41:17,301
You kill stuff which lets you level up, which lets you kill stuff easier.

712
00:41:17,922 --> 00:41:20,726
Again, sorry for the very simple, you know, oversimplification.

713
00:41:22,128 --> 00:41:24,751
Pushing against this, though, is the defensive advantage.

714
00:41:25,782 --> 00:41:28,003
So as you push into the person's territory,

715
00:41:28,403 --> 00:41:31,665
as you're gaining the advantage and you're able to attack more and more and you push

716
00:41:31,685 --> 00:41:35,086
towards their base, they gain a defensive advantage through the turrets which are

717
00:41:35,106 --> 00:41:35,927
helping them defend

718
00:41:36,287 --> 00:41:39,088
and the fact that they're closer to their base so they can get there faster

719
00:41:39,148 --> 00:41:40,149
after they respawn.

720
00:41:40,669 --> 00:41:44,151
And, you know, there's a whole bunch of mechanics there that give the defenders

721
00:41:44,211 --> 00:41:44,911
an advantage.

722
00:41:45,431 --> 00:41:49,313
And so you get this scenario where you have these two forces pushing against

723
00:41:49,413 --> 00:41:49,833
each other.

724
00:41:50,413 --> 00:41:56,118
You have the ever-increasing positive feedback loop of leveling up, leveling up, leveling up, getting stronger and stronger.

725
00:41:56,138 --> 00:41:59,440
And then that's getting it pushed in the other way from the defensive advantage.

726
00:41:59,880 --> 00:42:04,524
And you know, when you're pressing a defensive advantage, you probably get a few kills, so then you start to level up.

727
00:42:05,004 --> 00:42:08,446
And these two forces are kind of pushing back and forth against each other.

728
00:42:09,967 --> 00:42:13,710
And then at some point, maybe about 60-70% of the way through the game,

729
00:42:14,431 --> 00:42:15,331
you hit the tipping point.

730
00:42:16,235 --> 00:42:18,777
And all of a sudden, the positive feedback loop

731
00:42:19,277 --> 00:42:21,699
manages to overcome the defensive advantage.

732
00:42:22,119 --> 00:42:27,022
And after this point, the game is, in most scenarios,

733
00:42:27,122 --> 00:42:28,102
as good as lost.

734
00:42:28,522 --> 00:42:30,103
And the thing is, is this tipping point

735
00:42:30,664 --> 00:42:32,385
happens at a very specific time.

736
00:42:33,045 --> 00:42:35,306
Usually, experienced players especially,

737
00:42:35,366 --> 00:42:37,227
who can kind of see the entire game

738
00:42:37,267 --> 00:42:38,788
and understand everything that's going on,

739
00:42:38,828 --> 00:42:41,150
can see that moment when that happens.

740
00:42:41,650 --> 00:42:44,271
And all of a sudden, one side has the advantage.

741
00:42:46,284 --> 00:42:50,060
And the thing is, once you have that advantage, it's not like the game is over straight away.

742
00:42:50,984 --> 00:42:55,888
If you're on the losing side, you're now going to get your ass beaten for a solid five minutes.

743
00:42:56,069 --> 00:42:58,911
You're just going to get swarmed over and over and over.

744
00:42:59,432 --> 00:43:02,995
And you know, that really doesn't feel good. They really punish you once you hit that point.

745
00:43:03,335 --> 00:43:06,778
I mean, this is what it looks like when your Nexus is getting destroyed,

746
00:43:06,798 --> 00:43:10,441
and there's just so many minions and champs just all over you.

747
00:43:10,481 --> 00:43:13,544
You generally spawn and get completely destroyed instantly.

748
00:43:14,225 --> 00:43:17,808
And you can see this kind of positive feedback loop in this.

749
00:43:18,673 --> 00:43:21,536
I got this screenshot, you know, straight off Google images,

750
00:43:21,836 --> 00:43:24,218
and if you look up closely, you can see in the corner, you know,

751
00:43:24,339 --> 00:43:28,643
one player is just really pressing that advantage with the positive feedback loop

752
00:43:28,683 --> 00:43:30,485
and just getting kill after kill after kill.

753
00:43:32,200 --> 00:43:34,741
And to really rub salt into the wounds near the end.

754
00:43:36,261 --> 00:43:37,722
Oh, sorry, yeah, the blame game.

755
00:43:38,162 --> 00:43:40,022
If it happens at this particular tipping point,

756
00:43:40,183 --> 00:43:42,663
it's really easy to blame someone in particular, right?

757
00:43:43,083 --> 00:43:45,364
You know, you say, ah, if this person hadn't have done that thing,

758
00:43:45,484 --> 00:43:47,404
even though you'd been working together as a team

759
00:43:47,444 --> 00:43:49,125
for a solid half an hour, maybe,

760
00:43:49,885 --> 00:43:52,886
you hit that tipping point and all of a sudden it's one person's fault.

761
00:43:53,406 --> 00:43:57,087
And to make it worse, the best time for you to express that...

762
00:43:59,156 --> 00:44:02,918
is when you have the least amount of things competing for your attention,

763
00:44:03,238 --> 00:44:04,058
which is when you're dead.

764
00:44:04,678 --> 00:44:08,520
So if you've just died, you're probably not in a great state of mind

765
00:44:08,540 --> 00:44:12,222
and in a really good mood to be communicating with some other people.

766
00:44:15,583 --> 00:44:16,364
All of that said,

767
00:44:17,364 --> 00:44:19,425
I'm not going to let the players completely off the hook.

768
00:44:20,185 --> 00:44:22,747
The players definitely have to wear some of the responsibility.

769
00:44:23,707 --> 00:44:27,869
And for me, the example that sums this up the best of all games is Monopoly.

770
00:44:28,940 --> 00:44:32,783
So if you're like a nuclear 1950s family playing Monopoly,

771
00:44:32,983 --> 00:44:35,564
it's probably going to be quite, you know, quite nice.

772
00:44:35,604 --> 00:44:38,486
You're playing, it's pleasant, the rules, and you know,

773
00:44:38,546 --> 00:44:41,988
oh, you get some good wins and you get some unlucky losses

774
00:44:42,048 --> 00:44:42,849
and things like that.

775
00:44:43,589 --> 00:44:45,290
But then you play a game against Monopoly

776
00:44:45,310 --> 00:44:47,352
with a group of people who are all about those,

777
00:44:47,372 --> 00:44:50,474
like the under the table deals, the deal cutting,

778
00:44:50,514 --> 00:44:53,075
the, you know, the bargaining, the ransoms,

779
00:44:53,115 --> 00:44:54,476
you know, I'm taking this property

780
00:44:54,516 --> 00:44:56,477
and you've gotta pay me some exorbitant amount of money.

781
00:44:57,418 --> 00:45:00,639
That game is very different. It has a very different feeling.

782
00:45:00,920 --> 00:45:04,541
It really changes the game. The rules have stayed the same.

783
00:45:05,402 --> 00:45:08,303
But the players have changed and the game feels different.

784
00:45:08,403 --> 00:45:10,984
So I'm not going to let the players completely off the hook on this one.

785
00:45:11,004 --> 00:45:12,765
They definitely have some responsibility.

786
00:45:15,327 --> 00:45:18,628
So, getting towards the end here, I have some conclusions.

787
00:45:21,149 --> 00:45:22,930
Through all of this, I learned a lot.

788
00:45:24,463 --> 00:45:28,226
you know, I didn't just learn about game design through analyzing this and, you know,

789
00:45:28,607 --> 00:45:29,988
I just loved the fact that

790
00:45:30,348 --> 00:45:34,391
having to prepare for this talk really made me reflect on myself as a designer.

791
00:45:34,732 --> 00:45:37,814
So I learned a lot about game design in general and, you know,

792
00:45:38,074 --> 00:45:41,437
played some new games and, you know, really got to spend some time analyzing them.

793
00:45:41,537 --> 00:45:43,879
I learned a lot about players, about how they respond,

794
00:45:44,159 --> 00:45:47,582
about how players are really smart and really good at taking your rules and

795
00:45:47,662 --> 00:45:50,825
twisting them and coming up with ways to kind of subvert the game.

796
00:45:51,685 --> 00:45:53,727
But I also learned a lot about myself as a designer.

797
00:45:56,130 --> 00:45:57,652
Game design is really powerful.

798
00:45:57,672 --> 00:46:00,336
Like, really, really, really powerful.

799
00:46:00,456 --> 00:46:03,059
Just the pure mechanics of the game have the ability

800
00:46:03,680 --> 00:46:07,385
to completely change people and the way that they act.

801
00:46:08,026 --> 00:46:10,309
And I think this is something that I hadn't really respected

802
00:46:10,369 --> 00:46:11,731
before I did this prototype.

803
00:46:11,891 --> 00:46:13,834
I was, you know, as I said at the beginning.

804
00:46:15,084 --> 00:46:18,225
I wanted the game to be as engaging as possible at any cost.

805
00:46:18,965 --> 00:46:22,766
And I hadn't really thought about that that much and how well I would, you know,

806
00:46:22,946 --> 00:46:24,426
how compelling something could be

807
00:46:25,086 --> 00:46:28,307
and just how powerful the pure mechanics of the game could be.

808
00:46:28,907 --> 00:46:32,907
I was really thinking, you know, how could it have any possible problems?

809
00:46:33,288 --> 00:46:36,448
It's just little bits of whiteboard on some printed-off paper.

810
00:46:36,768 --> 00:46:38,609
How could it get that bad?

811
00:46:39,569 --> 00:46:41,989
Game design is very powerful, just the pure mechanics.

812
00:46:42,129 --> 00:46:44,230
And again, Neptune's Pride shows that as well.

813
00:46:45,551 --> 00:46:52,714
I learned a lot about players as well, about how they react, and how, I guess if anything,

814
00:46:52,794 --> 00:46:56,335
I learned how much I don't know about them and how unpredictable they are.

815
00:46:57,715 --> 00:47:02,877
And finally, I learned a lot about myself as well, and realized I'd never really taken

816
00:47:02,917 --> 00:47:08,519
time as a designer to stop and think and look kind of introspectively at what I was doing

817
00:47:08,779 --> 00:47:09,800
and what my goals were.

818
00:47:11,514 --> 00:47:20,117
After doing all this and doing all this process, you know, I really think, you know, I still want to make a very compelling, very engaging game, but I'm no longer willing to do it at any cost.

819
00:47:20,797 --> 00:47:30,240
If it's going to be compelling and engaging, the thing I want the players to take away from the game is the positive experiences they had. I want them to be at the pub talking about that great thing they did together

820
00:47:30,801 --> 00:47:34,102
and not kind of mourning over the terrible thing that happened to them.

821
00:47:35,462 --> 00:47:38,983
And for me, these are really, you know, my first steps. I've been doing game design for...

822
00:47:39,881 --> 00:47:42,382
not long compared to a lot of people, but six and a half years.

823
00:47:42,422 --> 00:47:46,704
This is really the first time I've thought hard about what I'm trying to achieve as a designer

824
00:47:47,264 --> 00:47:48,885
and, you know, where my limits are.

825
00:47:51,726 --> 00:47:53,707
The prototype, Tank Turns Tactics, will live on.

826
00:47:54,367 --> 00:47:56,048
I'm going to do it again at some point.

827
00:47:56,328 --> 00:47:58,629
I've actually tried to do it a couple of times, but

828
00:47:59,069 --> 00:48:02,010
I haven't figured out a way to do it without destroying the office again.

829
00:48:02,671 --> 00:48:05,712
One potential idea is to take it down to the university and destroy them.

830
00:48:08,447 --> 00:48:11,309
Alternatively, I could test it out at rival game companies.

831
00:48:11,529 --> 00:48:12,910
That might work out OK, too.

832
00:48:14,732 --> 00:48:17,533
But I want to change it to make it a more positive experience,

833
00:48:17,594 --> 00:48:18,094
eventually.

834
00:48:18,134 --> 00:48:20,435
I really think that there's something powerful here,

835
00:48:20,475 --> 00:48:23,037
and I've kind of accidentally stumbled across something

836
00:48:23,077 --> 00:48:23,838
really interesting.

837
00:48:24,218 --> 00:48:25,659
I just don't know how to get it there yet.

838
00:48:25,719 --> 00:48:27,360
I'm still thinking about it.

839
00:48:27,560 --> 00:48:29,842
I have some ideas, but yes.

840
00:48:31,583 --> 00:48:34,785
So anyway, that's my story about a crazy game experiment.

841
00:48:35,045 --> 00:48:37,367
It made me learn a lot, not about just games, but myself.

842
00:48:38,630 --> 00:48:43,414
I haven't really heard other people tell stories like this, I guess, and, you know, heard about

